    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-07-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-07-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="64"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d64">
                <head>64. National Security Study Memorandum 63<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d64fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Institutional
                        Files (H-Files), Box H–155, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> Files,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 63. Secret. A copy was sent to the
                        Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-07-03">July 3, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>U.S. Policy on Current Sino-Soviet Differences</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed a study of the policy choices confronting the United
                    States as a result of the intensifying Sino-Soviet rivalry and the current
                    Soviet efforts to isolate Communist China.</p>
                <p>The study should consider the broad implications of the Sino-Soviet rivalry on
                    the U.S., Soviet, Communist Chinese triangle and focus specifically on alternate
                    U.S. policy options in the event of military clashes between the Soviet Union
                    and Communist China.<note n="2" xml:id="d64fn2">Since the outbreak of
                        Sino-Soviet military clashes along the Ussuri River, the <gloss
                            target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_DIA1">DIA</gloss>
                        provided periodic intelligence updates of continued hostilities. (Central
                        Intelligence Agency, Executive Registry Subject Files, Job 93–T01468R, Box
                        2–4)</note>
                </p>
                <p>The study should also examine alternative policy approaches in the event of
                    continued intensification of the Sino-Soviet conflict short of a military
                    clash.</p>
                <p>The President has directed that the paper be prepared by an ad hoc group chaired
                    by a representative of the Secretary of State and including representatives of
                    the addressees of this memorandum and the Assistant to the President for
                    National Security Affairs.</p>
                <p>The study should be submitted to the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Review
                    Group by August 15.<note n="3" xml:id="d64fn3">A draft study was submitted on
                        September 3 and discussed at a meeting of the <gloss target="#t_WSAG1"
                            >WSAG</gloss> on September 4. The final version was completed on
                        November 10; see <ref target="#d101">Document 101</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
